{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01B5EgQ9ENfzuJo2U7CSmVGm","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Planfile build notes\n2\t\n3\t## Observations\n4\t\n5\t- 2026-05-15 [1.1.2] Task 1.1.1 (`bob_tools/planfile/__init__.py`) is marked\n6\t  `[x]` in CURRENT_PLAN.md, but the file does not exist on disk. Verified\n7\t  by `git show --stat dd60b01` and `git show --stat 54e117a`: the only\n8\t  files touched between the \"next: 1.1.1\" and \"next: 1.1.2\" checkpoints\n9\t  were CURRENT_PLAN.md, BUGS.md, and orchestra-run logs. The payload at\n10\t  `logs/orchestra-runs/4750dfe7db10/payloads/4750dfe7db10__edit__1.json`\n11\t  shows the agent returned \"I'll wait for your direction before\n12\t  starting\" and was nonetheless verdict-marked `complete`. Because 1.1.2\n13\t  creates sibling module files (not `__init__.py`), this session\n14\t  proceeded with the sibling files only; the package currently has no\n15\t  `__init__.py` despite the checkbox claiming otherwise. The user\n16\t  should decide whether to re-run 1.1.1 or accept a namespace package.\n17\t- 2026-05-15 [2.2.1-2.2.6] Same failure mode appears to have recurred at\n18\t  task 2.1.1-2.1.5 (heading parsers `_parse_heading`, `_parse_bugs_heading`,\n19\t  `_parse_h1`, `_parse_subsection`). The checkpoint commit\n20\t  `b608c08` is marked \"next: 2.1.1-2.1.5\" but no completion commit follows\n21\t  and `parser.py` was empty when this session (2.2.1-2.2.6) started. The\n22\t  orchestra log at `logs/orchestra-runs/f1af613fa1f2/log.jsonl` shows the\n23\t  edit state exited in 9 seconds with `output_chars: 38` and the editor\n24\t  said \"Ready. What would you like to work on?\" — the orchestrator\n25\t  still marked the state `complete` and advanced. Heading parsers will\n26\t  need to be retroactively implemented before the parser can be wired\n27\t  together; flagging for the user so the gap is not papered over.\n28\t- 2026-05-15 [2.4.2] `_attach_deps` reads \"immediately preceding task line\n29\t  at strictly lesser indent\" (from the task description) as: walk the\n30\t  open-ancestor stack from innermost to outermost and return the first\n31\t  task at lesser-or-equal indent — strict on `<`, lenient on `==`. The\n32\t  alternative reading — \"look only at the literally-immediately-preceding\n33\t  task and accept only if its indent is strictly less\" — would reject\n34\t  the case where @deps sits at indent 0 after a deeper child task in\n35\t  source order. Treating that as lenient attachment to the outer task\n36\t  matches what hand-written PLAN.md files seem to expect, but the design\n37\t  doc grammar only specifies position in the production (`DepsLine?`\n38\t  after the parent Item's `NL`); it does not state indent rules. Flagging\n39\t  in case the strict reading is preferred. No root-task fallback was\n40\t  added (unlike `_attach_ruledout`) because the task description does\n41\t  not mention one.\n42\t- 2026-05-15 [2.2.1-2.2.6] `_extract_annotations` distinguishes annotations\n43\t  from action tags by the mandatory whitespace after the colon: `[feat: x]`\n44\t  matches (whitespace after `:`), `[AUTO:run]` does not. This is the\n45\t  cleanest separator available given that both share the bracketed\n46\t  `key:value` shape and both could be observed as a trailing token. Per\n47\t  design doc grammar `Annot ← WS \"[\" Key \":\" WS Value \"]\"` the post-colon\n48\t  WS is required, so this is faithful to spec, not a workaround.\n49\t- 2026-05-15 [2.5.2] The state machine in `parse_plan` resolves a handful\n50\t  of ambiguities the design doc leaves open; flagging here so 2.5.4\n51\t  (syntax-error reporting) and strict mode in Stage 3 can revisit:\n52\t  1. Orphan tasks/`@deps`/`[RULEDOUT]` before any phase or Bugs heading\n53\t     are silently dropped. The grammar `Plan ← Magic Preamble? PhaseOrBugs+`\n54\t     forbids tasks outside a section, but mcloop's parser accepts them\n55\t     (with `stage=\"\"`). Strict mode should raise `PlanSyntaxError` here.\n56\t  2. A `###` subsection heading appearing inside a Bugs section is\n57\t     silently ignored (no scope change). The grammar\n58\t     `BugsSection ← \"##\" WS \"Bugs\" NL Item*` excludes subsections;\n59\t     strict mode could error.\n60\t  3. The phase `keyword` field is normalized to title case\n61\t     (`\"Stage\"` / `\"Phase\"`) regardless of how the heading was\n62\t     written. Design doc Q4 (\"How are Stage and Phase reconciled?\")\n63\t     recommends the canonicalizer not rewrite the keyword; if the\n64\t     canonical form must round-trip the original case, the parser\n65\t     needs to preserve it and a separate `keyword_original_case`\n66\t     field (or similar) becomes necessary. Left as title case for now\n67\t     because that's what the typed model needs and Q4 only constrains\n68\t     the rendered output.\n69\t  4. Stack is `clear()`-ed at every phase/Bugs/subsection boundary,\n70\t     matching mcloop. Consequence: an indented task immediately after\n71\t     a section heading becomes a root of the new section, not a child\n72\t     of any task in the previous section. Verified intentional via the\n73\t     `test_new_phase_resets_indent_stack` test.\n74\t\n75\t- 2026-05-15 [2.5.4] Compat-mode syntax errors are scoped narrowly. The\n76\t  task description says \"raise PlanSyntaxError on syntax violations in\n77\t  compat mode\", but most of the candidates (orphan tasks, prose outside\n78\t  accumulators, `### subsection` inside Bugs) have established mcloop\n79\t  precedent for being silently tolerated and so stay dropped in compat\n80\t  mode (deferred to strict mode in Stage 3, per the 2.5.2 NOTES entry).\n81\t  The one case that does raise in compat mode is an orphan `@deps` line\n82\t  with no preceding task to attach to: `@deps` is a planfile-introduced\n83\t  feature with no mcloop history, so there is no compat behavior to\n84\t  preserve, and the keyword has no semantic interpretation absent a\n85\t  target task. The `_raise_syntax_error` helper centralizes the\n86\t  message-quoting convention (backticks around the offending line) so\n87\t  Stage 3's strict-mode call sites can reuse the same format.\n88\t\n89\t- 2026-05-15 [2.5.5] Two cases listed in the Stage-2.5.5 task description do\n90\t  not match what compat-mode actually does, and the new\n91\t  ``TestParsePlanMinimalValidPlan`` class pins the actual behavior\n92\t  rather than the described one:\n93\t  1. \"a missing H1 raises\" — compat mode does not raise. mcloop's\n94\t     ``parse`` has no H1 concept at all, so there is no precedent to\n95\t     preserve, but our compat parser also chose silent tolerance\n96\t     (``project_title`` falls back to ``\"\"``). Strict mode in Stage 3\n97\t     should require an H1 and raise ``PlanSyntaxError`` on absence.\n98\t  2. \"tasks before any phase land in an implicit phase zero\" — the\n99\t     typed ``Plan`` model has no phase-zero slot, and ``Phase``\n100\t     requires an ordinal pulled from a heading. The 2.5.2 decision\n101\t     (documented above) was to drop orphan tasks silently to mirror\n102\t     mcloop's effective ``stage=\"\"`` behavior. Stage 3 strict mode\n103\t     will raise. If a future task asks us to actually surface these\n104\t     tasks somewhere, the typed model needs a new container (e.g. an\n105\t     orphan-tasks tuple on ``Plan``); deferring until that need is\n106\t     concrete.\n107\t\n108\t- 2026-05-15 [2.7.1-2.7.2] The Stage 2.7.1 task description listed eight\n109\t  rejection conditions for the new `tests/test_parser_rejections.py`:\n110\t  three structural (duplicate H1, multiple Bugs sections, duplicate\n111\t  phase/stage ordinals) and five tag-level (annotations with unclosed\n112\t  bracket, missing colon, or empty value; action tags without a colon\n113\t  or with an empty action name). Only the three structural anomalies\n114\t  raise in compat mode — every tag-level malformation is silently\n115\t  treated as prose by the parser today, and `[feat: ]` (the empty-value\n116\t  case) is in fact captured as a *valid* annotation because\n117\t  `_ANNOTATION_CONTENT_RE` only requires whitespace after the colon and\n118\t  permits an empty value. Per the [2.5.5] precedent of pinning actual\n119\t  behavior when the task description and the parser disagree, the new\n120\t  test module exercises the structural rejections with message/line\n121\t  assertions and uses a companion class to pin compat-mode tolerance of\n122\t  the tag-level cases. Stage 3 strict mode is the right place to add\n123\t  the rejections the task description anticipated.\n124\t\n125\t- 2026-05-16 [BUG from task 2.8] The BUGS.md entry filed against task 2.8\n126\t  was truncated by mcloop's `flat_obs[:200] + \"...\"` capture (see\n127\t  `mcloop/main.py:1218-1226`); the captured 200 chars covered only the\n128\t  python one-liner up to ``p.bugs is no`` and cut off the user's actual\n129\t  observation. Re-running the one-liner against all three target files\n130\t  (`/Users/mhcoen/proj/duplo/PLAN.md`, `/Users/mhcoen/proj/mcloop/PLAN.md`,\n131\t  `/Users/mhcoen/proj/mcloop/PLAN.EXAMPLE.md`) shows the parser succeeds\n132\t  cleanly with phase counts 8, 10, 2 and ``bugs is not None`` False for\n133\t  all three (none of those files has a literal ``## Bugs`` heading). The\n134\t  reproducible failure mode the bug entry *most likely* refers to is the\n135\t  ambiguity of the printed output: ``bugs=False`` is the same string for\n136\t  \"no Bugs section in the file\" and \"Bugs section is present but empty\",\n137\t  and task 2.8's stated expectations have ``mcloop/PLAN.md ... bugs=true``\n138\t  (which the file does not satisfy because mcloop keeps its bug list in a\n139\t  sibling ``BUGS.md`` file, not inside PLAN.md). The fix has two parts:\n140\t  (1) a new ``bug_count(plan) -> int`` in ``operations.py`` so callers\n141\t  can print a concrete count instead of the ambiguous bool, and (2) a\n142\t  manual verification helper at\n143\t  ``bob_tools/planfile/tests/manual/check_compat_read.py`` that the\n144\t  Stage 2 USER task can invoke with ``python -m\n145\t  bob_tools.planfile.tests.manual.check_compat_read`` to print\n146\t  ``OK <path> phases=<n> bugs=<true|false> bug_count=<n>`` per file\n147\t  (matching the helper-script task the user added in PLAN.md after this\n148\t  bug fired). Tests in ``TestBugCount`` pin the three states (no\n149\t  section, empty section, populated section) so the disambiguation\n150\t  cannot regress.\n151\t\n152\t## Hypotheses\n153\t\n154\t## Eliminated\n155\t\n156\t4026da1: Created six empty planfile modules (model.py, parser.py, renderer.py, operations.py, fileio.py, cli.py) with one-line docstrings as specified in the design. Discovered that task 1.1.1 was marked complete but never created the __init__.py file, documented this in NOTES.md. All four check commands (ruff check, ruff format, pytest, mypy) passed cleanly.\n157\t\n158\t91bc7df: Added test infrastructure for the planfile module. Created an empty __init__.py and a conftest.py with a fixtures directory pointer for future test fixtures. All code quality checks (ruff, pytest, mypy) passed successfully.\n159\t\n160\tee309dc: Added typed dataclasses for PLAN.md parsing model including TaskStatus enum, Task, Phase, Subsection, BugsSection, and Plan classes with frozen immutability. Created comprehensive test suite covering construction, frozen behavior, and exception formatting. All code quality checks (ruff, pytest, mypy) pass. The package currently functions as a namespace package without __init__.py as noted in existing documentation.\n161\t\n162\t3183a1b: Implemented the Stage 2 task-line recognizers and tag extractors in parser.py: the checkbox regex, a raw task-line record, and three extraction functions that strip leading flag tags (USER/BATCH), leading action tags (AUTO:<word>), and trailing key-value annotations from task text. Annotation disambiguation from action tags relies on the mandatory post-colon whitespace specified in the grammar. Added a test file with 251 lines covering each tag family in isolation, in combination, and in edge cases including nested brackets in annotation values and tag-like substrings that must remain prose. NOTES.md records that the heading-parser subtasks (2.1.1-2.1.5) were never executed due to a recurring orchestrator failure mode and will need to be implemented before the parser can be assembled into a full document parser.\n163\t\n164\t286741e: Added support for parsing RULEDOUT lines in the planfile parser. The implementation includes a regex pattern to match lines starting with [RULEDOUT] and a function that returns a structured record with indent, text, and line number. This matches mcloop's existing parse behavior where RULEDOUT lines are sibling lines attached to tasks by indentation. Tests verify proper handling of indented and top-level RULEDOUT lines, empty bodies, trailing whitespace stripping, and that non-leading occurrences are treated as prose.\n165\t\n166\t7b31ee0: Added RULEDOUT line attachment logic to match mcloop's behavior. The new function finds the nearest ancestor task with strictly less indent, falling back to the most recent root task when no such ancestor exists. Includes comprehensive tests covering edge cases like equal indents, empty stacks, and orphaned RULEDOUT lines. All linting, formatting, and type checks pass.\n167\t\n168\t2961b81: Added a regex constant `_DEPS_RE` to the planfile parser to recognize `@deps` lines containing whitespace-separated task IDs, following the design doc grammar. A new log file was created to record the implementation session.\n169\t\n170\t0941fdf: Added `_attach_deps` to the planfile parser, implementing the attachment logic for `@deps` sibling lines. The function walks the open-ancestor stack innermost to outermost, returning the parent task and a boolean indicating whether the attachment is lenient (same-indent) versus strict (lesser-indent); callers are expected to emit a validation warning for the lenient form. No root-task fallback is provided, unlike the existing RULEDOUT attachment. Seven unit tests cover the strict, lenient, innermost-wins, and outdented-walk cases, plus empty-stack and no-match edge cases. NOTES.md records the interpretation chosen for the ambiguous grammar rule, flagging it for review.\n171\t\n172\te346b0e: Implemented `validate_plan` in `operations.py`, which checks that every task ID listed in any `@deps` line resolves to a real task in the plan. The function walks all task containers (phases, subsections, and the bugs section) recursively, collects known IDs, then reports every missing reference in a single `PlanValidationError` rather than stopping at the first. Tasks without an explicit ID fall back to a source-line reference in the error message. A new test file covers the full range of cases: valid plans, unknown deps at root and nested levels, cross-section references, multi-error aggregation, and compat-mode tasks.\n173\t\n174\t704fc32: Added the public `parse_plan(text, *, strict=False, source_path=None) -> Plan` entry point to the planfile parser, establishing the API contract callers will use in subsequent stages. This stage wires only the signature: `strict` is accepted but unused, and the function returns an empty `Plan` that carries `source_path` through for future error reporting. The state machine that actually walks document text into phases, tasks, and bugs is deferred to the next increment. All four quality checks (ruff, pytest, mypy) pass with no regressions.\n175\t\n176\t001ec52: The parser now extracts the project title from the first H1 heading and accumulates prose in three distinct regions: the preamble (between the H1 and the first phase or bugs heading), phase prose (between a phase heading and its first task or subsection), and subsection prose (between a subsection heading and its first task). A new `_finalize_prose` helper trims leading and trailing blank lines while preserving internal paragraph breaks. Thirteen tests were added covering title extraction, multi-paragraph preambles, prose boundary behavior at tasks and subsections, and end-of-file finalization.\n177\t\n178\t142caa8: Added `_check_structural_sanity(lines, source_path)` to the planfile parser as a pre-parse corruption guard, mirroring mcloop's own check in `checklist.py`. The function scans raw lines for three anomalies observed in real PLAN.md corruption incidents: duplicate H1 titles with identical text, multiple Bugs sections at any heading level, and duplicate phase/stage ordinals. It is called at the start of `parse_plan()`, before any structural parsing, so the typed `Plan` model never has to represent a corrupted document. When anomalies are found, a single `PlanSyntaxError` is raised listing all of them with one-based line numbers so the user can fix everything in one pass. Ten new tests cover each anomaly in isolation, the H1/stage header disambiguation (a `# Phase 1:` line is classified as a stage header, not an H1), multi-error aggregation, source-path passthrough, and the clean-plan no-op path.\n179\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c61f1cb6-aab2-436d-a134-c2d01c95bc3d","uuid":"7a520d03-5a04-471d-9dd6-a5bd7f0b82fd","timestamp":"2026-05-16T13:48:54.724Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/mhcoen/proj/bob-tools/NOTES.md","content":"# Planfile build notes\n\n## Observations\n\n- 2026-05-15 [1.1.2] Task 1.1.1 (`bob_tools/planfile/__init__.py`) is marked\n  `[x]` in CURRENT_PLAN.md, but the file does not exist on disk. Verified\n  by `git show --stat dd60b01` and `git show --stat 54e117a`: the only\n  files touched between the \"next: 1.1.1\" and \"next: 1.1.2\" checkpoints\n  were CURRENT_PLAN.md, BUGS.md, and orchestra-run logs. The payload at\n  `logs/orchestra-runs/4750dfe7db10/payloads/4750dfe7db10__edit__1.json`\n  shows the agent returned \"I'll wait for your direction before\n  starting\" and